Dealing with missing data¶

We used 2 method to deal with the missing values which are present in the dataset.

1.Drop Missing values:

    If a feature contains more that 50% of the missing value then it better to drop that column as it will have very less or negetive impact on our model accuracy.

2.Filling Missing values:

    In this project we are taking the most frequent value of the feature and we are filling that value wherever we have msiing value
In [138]:
dropcol=[] #Dropping the columns having missing values more than 500
for col in train.columns:
    if train[col].isna().sum()>500:
        dropcol.append(col)
print(dropcol)

['Alley', 'FireplaceQu', 'PoolQC', 'Fence', 'MiscFeature']

le=LabelEncoder()

        i = train.columns.get_loc(k)
        train.iloc[:,i] = train.apply(lambda i:le.fit_transform(i.astype(str)), axis=0, result_type='expand')

Feature Selection¶

Curse of dimentionality:- model with the huge dimentionliy with 500-600 feature is less likly to perform well and the accuracy will be lower therefore it is very important to reduce and keep only those features who will improve models accuracy. In this project we have applied few feature selection techniques which are as follows

1. Variance¶

Dropping constant feature. If the feature is mostly same value, model is not going to learn anything from it

In [166]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import VarianceThreshold

2.Correlation of featuers with each other¶

If two of your feature is highly corelated, you can drop one because they are redundent

In [174]:
x_train=train.iloc[:,:-1]
In [175]:
matrix=x_train.corr().abs()
In [176]:
corr_pairs=matrix.unstack()
sorted_pairs = corr_pairs.sort_values(kind="quicksort")
negative_pairs = sorted_pairs[sorted_pairs>0.8]
negative_pairs = negative_pairs[negative_pairs!=1 ]
print(negative_pairs)
